📊 Task 3 
Log File Analysis with AWK, Grep & Sed
🛠️ Extracting Insights from Production Logs

---

🎯 Project Overview
In DevOps, logs are the heartbeat of an application.
Being able to parse thousands of lines of logs to find a single error is a critical skill. 
In this task, I analyzed the `Linux_2k.log` file to identify errors, extract timestamps, and redact sensitive information.

---

🛠️ Step-by-Step Implementation

1. Data Acquisition
I used the standard `Linux_2k.log` dataset from LogHub for this analysis.
```bash
wget [https://raw.githubusercontent.com/logpai/loghub/master/Linux/Linux_2k.log](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/logpai/loghub/master/Linux/Linux_2k.log)

2. Hunting for Errors (grep)
The first step in troubleshooting is finding where things went wrong.
Bash
grep -i "error" Linux_2k.log
Purpose: Filters all lines containing "error" (case-insensitive).

3. Extracting Timestamps & Log Levels (awk)
To get a cleaner view, I used awk to print only the specific columns needed.
Bash
awk '{print $1, $2, $3, $6}' Linux_2k.log
Purpose: Extracts the Month, Day, Time, and the Log Level/Service.

4. Security Masking / Redaction (sed)
For security compliance (like GDPR), IP addresses should often be hidden in shared logs.
Bash
sed -E 's/[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+/[REDACTED]/g' Linux_2k.log > redacted_linux.log
Purpose: Replaces all IPv4 patterns with the text [REDACTED].

🏆 Bonus Challenge: Frequency Analysis
I wanted to find the Top 10 most frequent log entries to identify recurring issues.
Bash
awk '{ $1=$2=$3=""; print $0 }' Linux_2k.log | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr | head -10

